#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:2
msgid "CPU support & SIMD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:4
msgid ""
"NumPy supports a wide range of platforms and CPUs, and includes a "
"significant amount of code optimized for specific CPUs. By default, NumPy "
"targets a baseline with the minimum required SIMD instruction sets that are "
"needed (e.g., SSE4.2 on x86-64 CPUs) and uses dynamic dispatch to use newer "
"instruction sets (e.g., AVX2 and AVX512 on x86-64) when those are detected "
"at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:10
msgid ""
"There are a number of build options that can be used to modify that "
"behavior. The default build settings are chosen for both portability and "
"performance, and should be reasonably close to optimal for creating "
"redistributable binaries as well as local installs. That said, there are "
"reasons one may want to change the default behavior, for example to obtain "
"smaller binaries, to install on very old hardware, to work around bugs, or "
"for testing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:17
msgid "To detect and use all CPU features available on your local machine::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:19
msgid ""
"$ python -m pip install . -Csetup-args=-Dcpu-baseline=\"native\" -Csetup-"
"args=-Dcpu-dispatch=\"none\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:21
msgid ""
"To use a lower baseline without any SIMD optimizations, useful for very old "
"CPUs::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:23
msgid "$ python -m pip install . -Csetup-args=-Dcpu-baseline=\"none\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/cpu_simd.rst:25
msgid ""
"For more usage scenarios and more in-depth information about NumPy's SIMD "
"support, see :ref:`cpu-build-options`."
msgstr ""
